cs.ET, cs.NE, cs.BI, cs.SY, cs.RO 

The paper discusses the use of a biological substrate, Physarum polycephalum, to implement logical operations and integrate living substrates into silicon hardware. This falls under the category of "emerging technologies" (cs.ET) and "neural and evolutionary computing" (cs.NE) as the slime mould is a single-celled organism with complex behavior. It also relates to "bioinformatics" (cs.BI) as the study of biological systems is involved. The use of the slime mould as a computing substrate also has implications for "systems and control" (cs.SY) and "robotics" (cs.RO) as it could potentially be used in the development of bio-inspired robots.
